+# PrintRequestHandlerRequest Object
+
+* `continue` Function - Continues the original print request. Prefer this for
+  synchronous allow-or-cancel decisions. This only works when called
+  synchronously before the print request handler returns.
+* `handle` Function - Handles the print request with an application-controlled
+  print job. Use this for asynchronous decisions that should later print with
+  `job.print(...)` or create a PDF with `job.toPDF(...)`.
+  * `handler` Function
+    * `job` [PrintRequestHandlerJob](print-request-handler-job.md)
diff --git a/docs/api/web-contents.md b/docs/api/web-contents.md
index 37b35d57dd..9e3c2b9937 100644
--- a/docs/api/web-contents.md
+++ b/docs/api/web-contents.md
@@ -1806,6 +1806,89 @@ win.webContents.print(options, (success, errorType) => {
 })
 ```
 
+#### `contents.setPrintRequestHandler(handler)`
+
+* `handler` Function | null
+  * `details` [PrintRequestHandlerDetails](structures/print-request-handler-details.md)
+  * `request` [PrintRequestHandlerRequest](structures/print-request-handler-request.md)
+
+Sets a handler for renderer-initiated print requests, such as `window.print()`.
+Passing `null` clears the handler.
+
+The handler may run asynchronous work before it handles `request`. This is useful
+when print options depend on frame state, for example when the app needs to call
+`details.frame.executeJavaScript(...)` before deciding how to print.
+
+Call `request.continue()` when the app can synchronously decide to allow the
+original print request to continue. Return without calling `request.continue()`
+or `request.handle(...)` to cancel it. Call `request.handle((job) => { ... })`
+to work with a
+[`PrintRequestHandlerJob`](structures/print-request-handler-job.md).
+Inside that callback, `job.print(options)` starts a new print operation for the
+frame that requested printing, and `job.toPDF(options)` creates a PDF for that
+frame. Both methods return Promises. Use `job.print(options)` when the app needs
+to wait asynchronously before deciding to print. Calling
+`request.handle(...)` synchronously before `handler` returns prevents Electron
+from continuing the original print request.
+
+If `request` is not handled before `handler` returns, Electron releases the
+renderer from the original `window.print()` call and cancels that original print
+request. This keeps renderer-dependent work such as
+`details.frame.executeJavaScript(...)` from deadlocking while the app decides
+what to do. In that asynchronous case, call `request.handle((job) => { ... })`
+later and use `job.print(options)` or `job.toPDF(options)` to handle the request.
+Continuing the original native print flow with `request.continue()` is only
+possible when `request.continue()` is called synchronously during `handler`.
+The `job` callback passed to `request.handle(...)` is run after Electron has
+released the original print request, so `job.print(options)` does not re-enter
+the renderer while it is still blocked in the original `window.print()` call.
+
+Prefer `request.continue()` for synchronous allow-or-cancel decisions. Prefer
+`request.handle(..., job.print(...))` for asynchronous decisions that should
+still print. `job.print(options)` uses the same print option path and has the
+same platform limitations as `webContents.print(options)`, but it targets the
+frame that originally requested printing.
+
+```js
+const { BrowserWindow } = require('electron')
+
+const win = new BrowserWindow()
+
+win.webContents.setPrintRequestHandler(async (details, request) => {
+  const html = await details.frame.executeJavaScript(
+    'document.documentElement.outerHTML'
+  )
+  const options = await decidePrintOptions(details.url, html)
+
+  request.handle(job => {
+    job.toPDF(options).then(pdf => {
+      console.log('PDF size:', pdf.length)
+    })
+  })
+})
+```
+
+To decide asynchronously and then print without using the original native print
+continuation, call `job.print(options)`:
+
+```js
+win.webContents.setPrintRequestHandler(async (details, request) => {
+  const options = await getPrintOptions(details)
+
+  request.handle(async job => {
+    try {
+      await job.print(options)
+    } catch (error) {
+      console.error(error)
+    }
+  })
+})
+```
+
+`request.continue()` or `request.handle(...)` may be called at most once for each
+print request. If `request.handle(...)` is called asynchronously, the original
+print request has already been released.
+
 #### `contents.printToPDF(options)`
 
 * `options` Object
